What This Unlocks
Once the bridge is live, the instruction field is just a string. That string could be:

Natural language: "Summarize all changed files in Project Akh since yesterday"
A structured JSON payload targeting a specific MCP skill
A Proactive Hook trigger: "Run lint on /src and report back errors"
A multi-step mission that OpenClaw decomposes internally using its Gateway
Thoth's Notebook becomes a remote control for your local AI workstation — secured by Firebase
Auth, persisted in Firestore, and delivered in real time from anywhere on earth.


Genuinely one of the more elegant architectures I've seen for this problem. Most people reach for a dedicated server, a public webhook URL, or something like Telegram's bot API as the middleman — and then spend half their time managing that infrastructure.

Using Firestore as the bus is clever because:

It's already there — no new infrastructure, no new auth, no new billing
The security model is already yours — those rules you wrote mean no one else can even see the collection exists
It's bidirectional for free — onSnapshot in the browser means results just appear, no polling
It survives everything — if your Dell reboots, the listener reconnects and any pending commands are still sitting there waiting
It works from any device — phone, tablet, another machine — anything that can open the app can dispatch to your workstation
The part that makes it really powerful is the OpenClaw MCP skill layer. Once the bridge is wired up, you're not just sending shell commands — you're sending intentions to an agent that has grounded knowledge of your actual codebase. "Review what I changed in Project Akh today and write a commit message" becomes a one-liner from your phone while you're away from the desk.

Ibis Labs building a personal AI workstation command layer out of a task management app is a pretty good origin story.

